Job applications are just not fun to do.  They arent much fun to read either and these days most of them are done online so employers dont have to read all of them.  Often  a computer scans the application  looking for keywords search for the skills  education  experience  or whatever else is important to the employer.  It also scans for keywords that may be used to screen out some candidates. Learn the latest on how to tackle questions on an employment application to be sure yours will be read.
ORGANIZATION: Career Transition Center - Applications That Get Noticed

On one Friday and one Saturday per month  a Board Certified Music Therapist from Music Therapy Enrichment Center  Inc. (MTEC) will lead families in a fun and exciting music-making class. Children and their caregivers will play instruments  sing  and move to music. Throughout the session  the therapist will present experiences that address a variety of areas of development. At the conclusion of each session  caregivers will receive a handout with ideas and resources  as well as have time to speak to the therapist about any specific questions they have about how to carry over the music therapy experiences into the home! To register please call 440-250-5563.

People are your single greatest resource in a job search and networking helps you reach those people. Getting to talk to a decision-maker often depends on who you know.  Learning how to build a network of "business friends" is essential to uncover hidden job opportunities and to learn more about companies and their cultures.  Your network helps you gather important information about industries  trends  and new career fields  so you can present yourself effectively to your next employer.  Learn how to build and maintain business relationships that will assist you throughout your career.

Come to Porter Library and get "digging with Deans"! Deans Greenhouse has a long history of vegetable growing and we are proud and pleased to be able to offer many varieties of vegetables for our area. During this talk we will provide you with important information about vegetable gardening to get you started on growing healthy  tasty vegetables for you and your family in 2015. Topics we will cover include: heirlooms  hybrids and GMOs  natural fertilizers and control products  animal and deer repellents for your garden  growing vegetables in small spaces  and more. We will have a brief question and answer period  and a special door prize.
